context: In the nineteenth and twentieth centuries the RIBA and its members had a leading part in the promotion of architectural education in the United Kingdom, including the establishment of <a0_0><b5_0>the Architects' Registration Council of the United Kingdom<b5_0/><a0_0/> (ARCUK) and <a1_0><b6_0>the Board of Architectural Education under the Architects (Registration) Acts, 1931 to 1938<b6_0/><a1_0/>. A member of the RIBA, Lionel Bailey Budden, then Associate Professor in <a2_0>the <b7_0>Liverpool University School of Architecture<b7_0/><a2_0/>, had contributed the article on Architectural Education published in the fourteenth edition of the <a3_0><b8_0>Encyclopædia Britannica<b8_0/><a3_0/> (1929). His School, Liverpool, was one of the <a4_0><b9_0>twenty<b9_0/><a4_0/> schools named for the purpose of constituting the statutory Board of Architectural Education when the 1931 Act was passed.
